A brief biographical sketch of the shooter:

Vanessa — alias/codename "Maneater" — Bonë Whîte[$ "double barrel" last name, composed of two words separated by a space][@ this surname I lifted from a conversation spurred by the "Èsor" below, where I said "Tasteful diacritic reversal, very nice", and then C said "Let's see Paul Allen's diacritical", and then I invented this name. This is an _American Psycho_ business card scene reference.] was born at the tender age of 0[$ ever since Groucho Marx, this has been the traditional way to start a biography in the culture of the flying island — and the island postdates him considerably] to two-and-a-half loving parents. After a fascinating and obscure series of events that won't be gone into here, she acquired what the kids are calling "The Curse Of La Regla"[$ distinct from the normal "La Regla", of course]:

Although blind by eye, this female super soldier, has a sort of omniscient uterine third sight, that allows her to omnisciently locate[@ And identify? Or at least distinguish in some capacity. ~C] all men, but only when she's ovulating. And it only works on fecund males.

[@ *Holy—* ~C]

[@ %% could create a twist where an infertile man (could be Lars, depending on how deep his "loss of appetite" is?) sneaks up on her "invisibly". ~M ❡ “Hinder me? Thou fool. No living man may hinder me!” ~C ❡ “Lady, I haven’t been ‘living’ for 30 years.” Shoots her unceremoniously. ~C]

Scientific name of this power? Ovniscience[@ —C ~M]

Slogan? _Time of death: my time of the month_ [@ —C ~M] [@ Good one ~M]

She wore an eyepatch over both eyes. And also as a sort of brassière-type fashion item. Actually a lot of her outfit was eyepatch themed.

Her favorite type of wine was Èsor[@ This is "Rosé" backwards, which was invented by C ~M], but she could never remember its name — not being a heavy wine drinker, and so she fumbled over the words, calling it things like "Eeyore"[@ J immediately said this upon reading "Èsor" ~M][@ 🫏 ~M][@ 🫏 ~C] or "Eyesore". But that's neither here nor there.

︼[$end digression bracket]

What was here or there[@ A reference outside the digression bracketing to something _inside_ the digression bracketing? lemongrab_unacceptable.gif ~C], however, was Thomas and the assassin, who were rapidly coming into co-location on the ground.

Thomas raised[$rose?] up his hand at the assassin and yelled "TRACK VISION!"[@ This is getting silly. ~C] and thereby learned all this instantly. Maneater detected him by third sight (a vivid and geometric affair, like night vision in a 90s movie made with primitive CGI) and fired a hurried shot directly in his direction, which was luckily prevented from hitting Thomas by him stumbling over a particularly prominent ground-branch.

Panicked, Maneater grabbed a rope ladder that dangled by her from a Stealth Helicopter[$"Completely silent or your money back!"™], and lifted off. Attempting escape.[$Unlike most of the characters in his novel, who are attempting escapades.]

[C; 1220 words]

Thomas turned his stumble into an ungainly but serviceable roll, and after a moment to regain his balance, he resumed his charge. For a moment. Then, as he processed that his quarry was ascending and would be beyond his reach before he could possibly reach her[$and in a manner of speaking was therefore already beyond his reach], he slowed to a walk and stopped almost directly beneath Maneater.

He looked up at her. She utered down at him[$ Another advantage of her sensing modality is 4π steradian coverage. Thomas had to crane his neck to keep her in sight, but she did not have to crane _anything_ to continue monitoring[$ One might call it Pre=baby-Monitoring] his position.].

Thomas noted that the helicopter did not have any windows. Maneater had replaced them with additional armor plating.

Her Mburu-Braun T59[$fuuUUuuture] still had a few rounds in the magazine[$but not _too_ future], and its barrel was once again pointed at Thomas's chest.

"...my eyes are up here," Thomas said, when he was still alive after a couple seconds. "Aren't you supposed to aim between them?"

"Your eyes are _down there_," Maneater[@ At first I wrote this as 'Manewater'. A single W can change the whole. Much to think won.] corrected. "And I've never had much occasion to concern myself with men's eyes. Or with what I'm supposed to do."

This last wasn't entirely true, though you probably wouldn't call it a lie either. Like a pie's crust, 'supposed' can hide the apples of classical virtue, or the stew-meat-and-potatoes of the social contract, or the peaches of personal idealism, or the mixed berries of cultural norms, or the pork of bureaucracy. Or kumquats.[^$pie]

[^$pie]: Look, some metaphors[@ I feel that similes are a kind of metaphor.] are insightful and piquant and destined to rewire your synapses, and some get shoved in because just describing the action gets stale after a while[$ Piquant, stale, maybe this is a cool literary metaphor after all.]. 

Maneater, as a mercenary, did find conscience[$ I'm going with cherries.] a bit of a hindrance and when on the job tended to leave it behind, with plenty of water and the AC and its favorite music on. But, as a mercenary, she _did_ concern herself with carrying out her assignments, with understanding how her employer understood their relationship, with maintaining her reputation.

And, as a mercenary, she concerned herself with something else. Most do. Most assassins, enforcers, and assorted career criminals obey some rule not dictated by the game theory of their profession. They might be honorable, or draw the line at killing children, or something more orthogonal to virtue, like appreciating fine art or a good hunt. It is difficult for humans to maintain an attitude of rigid adherence to the meta of their material system, for good reason, and those who can do so usually find colder, more ruthless careers than assassination, such as banking[@ This feels kind of cliche, but I'm going with it. If either of you can think of a more interesting job to put here I'm open to it.].

Maneater hunted down and killed men[$ Not out of misandry: she liked men well enough non-professionally, she was just much, much better at killing them than women.]. She found them and removed them. She was the agent; they were things to finish[^$innuendos]. The nose of her helicopter was bare; she didn't have a decal for every person she killed for the same reason you don't put a notch in your belt every time you load[$ hur hur hur, "load".] the dishwasher[$If we were being chauvinist, we might say "put a notch in your bedpost every time you load the dishwasher." Eh? Eh? Eh...maybe you had to be there. Like your mom! Heyooooo!].

[^$innuendos]: stupid innuendos lancing through every aspect of our language. I tried 'do', 'finish', 'complete'. Should I just say 'bang' and have done? Like, shoot with a gun, bang? They were things to bang.

Well, also she wouldn't be able to see them.

On this job, Maneater had _missed_. _Every time_. And this man had run toward _her_. Recklessly, yes, but still. This job wasn't like her other jobs. And so it shouldn't end like her other jobs. Respect? Eh, that's harder to say. But she slid Tiffany[$ as she called her T59] back into her[$Tiffany's[$Although the lease was under Bonë Whîte, Vanessa.].] holster[$ She'd tried to keep the eyepatch theme going with the holsters but sometimes you have to let function win.].

Thomas exhaled[$ Good thing the helicopter is a Stealth Helicopter or you wouldn't have been able to read that over the noise of the blades.]. "Thank God."

"Damn it." Ms. Bonë Whîte groaned. "This is gonna be such a hassle." Her voice was deep and smooth. When she sang, which she did beautifully and infrequently, she was a tenor. She reached for an eyepatchy pack strapped to her thigh and pulled out her iPatch[$ Never let it be said that I had good taste in anything. ~C], which she used to "patch in" and control various electronic systems, including her helicopter when she was not in it. Or sometimes when she was in it and didn't feel like bending forward. She belayed her ascent.

Thomas, while denied the guided insight afforded the reader by means of this narration, had been getting existential in his own direction (in parallel with the more practical fear of annihilation, which was now largely lifted). "How does it work? What you can do?"

Maneater shrugged, still holding to the ladder with one hand. "They don't really go into the mechanics of it with us."

Thomas watched the words _Recommended by 9/10 Librarians_ scroll across the hazy warping circle of the Stealth Helicopter's blades, partially obscured by Maneater's head. In that moment, undirected by the Track, he asked about the wrong pronoun. "Us?"[@ But is 'they' or 'it' the right pronoun? who knows! you should ask him.]

Maneater shrugged again. "I imagine you'll meet more of us soon enough."

Thomas thought that he might be included in that 'us'. Fear of a different kind was settling on him like snow. "Why...why can I do what I can do? _Why have I not asked that before?_" he whispered[$ Again, the Stealth Helicopter comes in very handy from a narrative standpoint, as Maneater would not be able to hear him without it[$"OwlTech Anti-Noise Contouring Included on Every Surface!"].].

"I'm not killing you right this second," Maneater said flatly. "That doesn't mean we're _friends_, Metcalf. I'm not going to answer your questions. I'm going to fly away, drink a fair bit, and figure out how to explain this."

Thomas stared at her. Then gazed at her. Then spoke slowly. "Try 'The Mills of God'[@https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mills_of_God]. Capital T 'The', Capital M, 1, capital L, capital L, 5, lowercase 'of', capital G, 0, capital D. That should grant you access."

_People are making a big noise over these 'copters, but you won't hear it from us!_ shimmered holographically between them and the sky.

Vanessa closed her mouth. Opened it again. Closed it again. Eventually, she said, hoarsely, and equally slowly, "The last place I felt Paul Eeny was 1440 Ratcliffe Court. I...can't feel him anymore. I'm sorry." Maneater tried to harden her expression a little, with marginal success. "You should leave. Stop looking, get out of this. If we meet again, I will kill you, Thomas."

She tensed, touched the iPatch, and the helicopter roared soundlessly up and away.

As he watched her bleakly, Thomas felt a slight twinge of nausea, and knew she was telling the truth.

Nah, just kidding. The Track does seem to have quasi-oracular properties, but it just guides Thomas. It doesn't confirm ominous pseudo-threats[@which phrase I stole from the webcomic Paranatural.].

Still. Pretty ominous.


